text: I think the really interesting thing about option markets in that regard is that they really are not a zero-sum game in the way that you might think about certain investors trying to be smarter than the other guy in terms of whether Apple is too cheap or Netflix is too expensive. Really, option markets, in a sense, there's a large need to provide liquidity for end users of option markets and distribute risk from where options are being heavily supplied to where they're being heavily demanded. So option markets and derivatives in general, the markets exist because there are end users who are trying to achieve certain objectives. There's portfolio hedgers who are trying to protect their positions. There are large pension funds trying to generate income by selling options. There are, outside of equities, there are corporations trying to hedge their currency and their commodity exposures, for example. So these markets really developed on the back of end user demand and end user need to transform. That's for risk. And the key thing in relative value investing and in volatility is that the marginal price setter for the probabilities and the market prices that we think about and talk about, typically that marginal price setter is not a volatility investor that's thinking about nuances in implied volatility pricing. Typically, it's an end user of options and derivatives. So it's a huge pension fund that's running a call overwriting program or maybe a retail investor. So you know, a lot of these end users are just a potential investor buying a structured note linked to the price return of European equities, for example. These end users have their own objectives. They're typically, you know, more structural long term objectives as part of a larger portfolio that aren't necessarily focused on the exact price that they're paying for an exact type of risk or a particular volatility skew parameter. They may just not focus on those things, right. So for a specialist volatility investor. Many of the best opportunities really arise from either explicitly or implicitly providing liquidity to meet the needs of end users and to warehouse basis risk between what they're buying and what they're selling.
